ey identify—and assess—each claim, weighing in on whether the specter of being “caught on tape” is capable of changing a criminal justice system desperately in need of reform. Cops, Cameras, and Crisis is a must-read for policymakers, police leaders, and activists interested in twenty-first-century policing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPolice misconductxPrevention. 0aPolice-community relations. 0aPolice. 0aWearable video devices. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aBig data.  aBody-worn camera adoption.  aCitizen privacy.  aCrisis in policing.  aDiffusion of Innovation.  aEvidence-based policing.  aFacial recognition.  aOfficer proactivity.  aPolice legitimacy.  aPolice technology.  aUse of force.1 aMalm, Aili, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479865864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479865864.jpg  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK